<!-- The main area starts with a homepage hero, then moves into study sections that map out the whole site. -->
  <main id="main-content" class="page-shell">
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Project homepage</p>
          <h1>Web Servers and HTTP: How the Web Really Works Behind the Scenes</h1>
          <p class="subhead">This site explains how browsers, DNS, HTTP, and web servers work together to load modern webpages. It starts with my original research paper and expands it into a cleaner, more visual study website.</p>
          <div class="badge-row" aria-label="Key terms">
            <span class="badge">Web Server</span>
            <span class="badge">HTTP</span>
            <span class="badge">HTTP/3</span>
            <span class="badge">DNS</span>
            <span class="badge">Caching</span>
            <span class="badge">HTTPS</span>
          </div>
          <div class="metric-grid">
            <div class="stat-box">
              <h3>Main focus</h3>
              <p>How browsers and servers communicate to deliver web content.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-box">
              <h3>What changed</h3>
              <p>More content, more references, cleaner structure, and stronger page styling.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-box">
              <h3>Site contents</h3>
              <p>8 pages with topic guides, a glossary, a quiz, and expanded resources.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a class="button-link" href="how-it-works.html">Start with the request cycle</a>
            <a class="button-secondary" href="quiz.html">Take the quiz</a>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="figure-card">
          <img src="images/request-response.png" alt="Diagram showing a browser contacting DNS and a web server before receiving an HTTP response.">
          <figcaption>A page request may feel instant, but the browser still has to find the server, ask for files, and render the response.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="page-section content-card">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <h2>Abstract</h2>
        <p>This project explains the systems that make ordinary browsing possible.</p>
      </div>
      <p>The web feels simple from the user side, but a lot happens underneath that clean experience. A browser has to resolve a domain name, open a network connection, send an HTTP request, receive a response, and then assemble many files into one visible page. This site focuses on the two technologies at the center of that process: web servers and HTTP. It also shows how HTTP evolved from a basic document protocol into a faster system built for media-heavy and interactive websites.</p>
      <p>In this improved version of the site, I added more explanation about DNS, HTTPS, server responsibilities, latency, caching, reverse proxies, and content delivery. I also cleaned up the layout so each page is easier to scan and study.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="page-section">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <h2>What you will learn</h2>
        <p>Each topic page focuses on one part of the bigger picture.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cards-grid">
        <article class="mini-card">
          <h3>1. How a request moves</h3>
          <p>Follow the path from a typed URL to DNS lookup, server processing, and page rendering.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="mini-card">
          <h3>2. Why HTTP changed</h3>
          <p>See how HTTP/0.9, 1.0, 1.1, 2, and 3 each solved new performance problems.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="mini-card">
          <h3>3. What servers do today</h3>
          <p>Look at server software, HTTPS, caching, reverse proxy work, and back end connections.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="page-section two-column">
      <article class="content-card">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <h2>Key terms</h2>
          <p>A few important ideas appear across the whole site.</p>
        </div>
        <dl class="definition-list">
          <div>
            <dt>Web Server</dt>
            <dd>A machine or software service that stores resources and returns them to clients.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>HTTP</dt>
            <dd>The application protocol browsers and servers use to exchange web resources.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>DNS</dt>
            <dd>The naming system that maps human-readable domains to IP addresses.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>Latency</dt>
            <dd>The delay between a request being sent and the response starting to arrive.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </article>

      <article class="content-card">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <h2>Table of contents</h2>
          <p>Use these pages like a short study guide.</p>
        </div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="how-it-works.html">How the request and response cycle works</a></li>
          <li><a href="http-evolution.html">How HTTP developed from HTTP/0.9 to HTTP/3</a></li>
          <li><a href="web-servers.html">How web servers evolved and what they do today</a></li>
          <li><a href="key-concepts.html">A larger glossary of core web concepts</a></li>
          <li><a href="quiz.html">A self-assessment quiz with instant scoring</a></li>
